TY  - JOUR
AB  - We investigate political determinants of land reform implementation in the Indian state of West Bengal. Using a village panel spanning 1974&#x2013;1998, we do not find evidence supporting the hypothesis that land reforms were positively and monotonically related to control of local governments by a Left Front coalition vis-&#xe0;-vis the right-centrist Congress party, combined with lack of commitment to policy platforms. Instead, the evidence is consistent with a quasi-Downsian theory stressing the role of opportunism (reelection concerns) and electoral competition.
